    "text": "Yeah, this is the kind of thing I like to do recently. As I mentioned to you, probably, that I like to write, as well as paint. And this is from an article in which I talk about art and medicine. And here is the writer, of course, in the middle. The snake represents life and [PAUSES FOR 3 SECONDS] blood. And the-- the-- from the tail of the snake is come out the hand of the surgeon. When he cuts the snake, the life goes down on his scalpel. And from the head of the snake is coming out an artist hand, who actually is painting the snake. So the whole thing is just a flow. There's no separation, and this is what life is about. We're just part of something from previous and we're going to do obligation and something else taking over. [PAUSES FOR 4 SECONDS] Every Christmas and before New Year, I write an article and I illustrate. This is one of them. But actually, the concept comes from the book of the And what it is in the book, in a simpler fashion, that 6 million people are one little dot, like here. And then from there is the light, became bigger and bigger. And the bad thing around them, the darkness, will disappear. This is that from that concept. And here is the same thing. Here is the center from the light. The light going up and eventually became bigger and bigger and became more meaningful. The Holocaust is, besides the bad things what happened, eventually some good is could happen, such as the establishment of Israel and new life can flourish. [PAUSES FOR 6 SECONDS] I think that the person who survived like myself the Holocaust, has an additional obligation besides survival. I have-- we have to tell people that the only difference it makes is the changes you can do it within yourself. I have the opportunity of an incredible way to communicate with children through my book and my lectures. I'm talking to them and I will be able to have some impact on them. I think that's, again, the most important thing I can learn from the Holocaust and I can teach people from the Holocaust. And that is namely, again, what I think the most important-- you have to stand up for your right and to remain human even if the circumstance is inhumane. And I hope you learned some positive lesson from the Holocaust besides the sorrow we all have for those who were killed, like my father and many other millions. Thank you very much.",
